This is the amount written off directly to Profit & Loss of the value of the reporting party's investments that result in an exposure to the asset class of commercial property.
Commercial property exposure is defined according to the nature of the risk. An exposure should be classified as commercial property risk, if the exposure is subject to the performance of the commercial property market. This exposure does not include property used for the reporting party's own operational use.
Expense Write Off Direct Exposure Property Commercial Amount

This is the amount written off directly to Profit & Loss of the value of the reporting party's investments that result in an exposure to the asset class of industrial commercial property.
Industrial property exposure is defined according to the nature of the risk. An exposure should be classified as industrial property risk, if the exposure is subject to the performance of the industrial property market. This exposure does not include property used for the reporting party's own operational use.
Industrial commercial property may include for example, warehouses and factories.
Expense Write Off Direct Exposure Property Commercial Industrial Amount

This is the amount written off directly to Profit & Loss of the value of the reporting party's investments that result in an exposure to the asset class of land development.
land development property exposure is defined according to the nature of the risk. This exposure does not include property used for the reporting party's own operational use.

This is the amount written off directly to Profit & Loss of the value of the reporting party's investments that result in an exposure to the asset class of tourism and leisure property.

An exposure should be classified as tourism and leisure property risk, if the exposure is subject to the performance of the property market for tourism, leisure or hospitality. This exposure does not include property used for the reporting party's own operational use.
Tourism & leisure commercial property may include for example, hotels, motels and lodgings, recreational and sporting facilities, hotel developments, time-share developments and other hospitality industries.

This is the amount of any income actually received during the relevant period from all exposures of the reporting party that give rise to counterparty credit risk, determined in accordance with the relevant prudential standards, where: (a) the estimates of future interest income are not zero; (b) no specific provision for impairment has been raised in respect of it; and (c) the original contractual terms have been modified via a formal (written) agreement to provide for concessions of interest or principal for reasons related to the financial difficulties of the counterparty, rendering the facility non-commercial to the reporting party. In considering whether a facility is non-commercial, the reporting party needs to consider whether it would extend credit on similar terms and conditions to a new counterparty exhibiting similar risk characteristics.

This is the net value of realised gains and losses in relation to the disposal of derivatives during the relevant period.
Derivatives are generally defined as those instruments/contracts, where the value is based on other products, and/or on prices associated with financial products. Derivative contracts involve: - Future delivery, receipt or exchange of financial items such as cash or another derivative instrument; or - Future exchange of real assets for financial items where the contract may be tradeable and has a market value. The contracts can either be binding on both parties (e.g. as with a currency swap) or subject to the exercise by one party of a right contained within the contract (as with options).
This item excludes foreign exchange gains (losses) from currency conversions of derivatives.
Income Realised Gain Loss Derivatives Net Amount
